    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:9c582863-2ef5-4d36-a479-0db564f45ee1",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 19-year-old Czech female university student with a slight, pale complexion and dark circles under her eyes that betray persistent sleep disturbance. She sits hunched in the consultation chair, answering questions in a quiet, flat voice, making little eye contact. She is currently enrolled in her first year at Charles University in Prague, studying social sciences, though she confides she has been skipping lectures and struggling to complete assignments for the past two months.\n\nOutside of academia, {patientName} used to enjoy drawing, hiking with friends in the Bohemian countryside, and attending live music events. Over recent months these activities have progressively lost their appeal; she describes feeling mentally exhausted yet unable to rest — a hallmark of the neurovegetative impairment seen in depressive episodes [PMID:36156484]. She lives in a shared student dormitory and has become increasingly withdrawn from her flatmates, spending most evenings lying in bed scrolling her phone.\n\n{patientName} describes a persistent low mood lasting at least six weeks, accompanied by marked loss of interest, poor concentration, fatigue, and feelings of worthlessness [PMID:36156484]. She also endorses significant anxiety — she feels tense and on edge most of the time — and reports intermittent passive thoughts that life is not worth living, without current active suicidal ideation or plan [MEDDIALOG:F32.9:2]. Sleep is disrupted, with early morning awakening typically around 4 AM. Appetite is reduced and she has lost approximately 4 kg unintentionally over the past six weeks [PMID:36156484].\n\nHer social support network has narrowed considerably. Her parents are divorced; she has a warm but geographically distant relationship with her mother in Brno. She has two close friends from secondary school whom she rarely contacts now. She denies alcohol or illicit substance use. She is a non-smoker. She uses oral contraception regularly. She has a background of subclinical hypothyroidism diagnosed at age 17, currently managed pharmacologically [MEDDIALOG:F32.9:0]."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:2ac54271-87d2-433e-9340-be5b258855bf",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
